How REST API is Stateless (Project Example)
Step 1Ô∏è‚É£ User logs in

User logs in

Server gives a token

Step 2Ô∏è‚É£ User requests notes

Frontend sends:

Token

API request

Server checks token ‚Üí sends notes ‚Üí forgets user

Step 3Ô∏è‚É£ User edits a note

Frontend again sends:

Token

API request

Server again checks token ‚Üí updates note ‚Üí forgets user

üëâ Server does NOT remember:

Who you are

What you did before

Every request starts fresh
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Real-Life Example (Very Easy)
ATM Machine üí≥

You insert card ‚Üí enter PIN ‚Üí withdraw money

ATM does not remember you after transaction

Next time ‚Üí you must insert card + PIN again

üëâ That is stateless
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Why REST API is Stateless?

Simple reasons:

More secure

Easy to scale

Server does not store user info
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Tricky Interview Question
Q. If REST is stateless, how does login work?

Answer (Simple):
Login works using token. Token is sent in every request.
